ðŸ”¹What is Metagoofil?

    -Metagoofil is an OSINT tool that harvests publicly-available office documents from a target domain (PDF, DOC, XLS, PPT, etc.), downloads them, and extracts metadata (authors, usernames, software versions, OS, paths, e-mail addresses, and other artifacts) using tools like exiftool.

    -Itâ€™s useful for passive information gathering: what employees produce, software versions exposed in docs, or internal usernames that leak in metadata.

ðŸ”¹Why use Metagoofil?

    -To discover sensitive info leaked in document metadata (usernames, emails, company paths).

    -To build targeted wordlists (usernames/paths) for later testing (password sprays, phishing) during authorized engagements.

    -To augment reconnaissance with artifacts you wouldnâ€™t find via simple HTTP sweeps.

    -Important for defenders to audit what sensitive metadata is publicly exposed.

ðŸ”¹How to install (Kali)

Metagoofil is shipped in Kali repositories. Install with:

    sudo apt update
    sudo apt install metagoofil

ðŸ”¹Basic usage (syntax)

    metagoofil -d <domain> -t <types> -l <limit> -n <threads> -o <output_dir>

ðŸ”¹Common options explained:

    1. -d <domain> â†’ target domain (required).

    2. -t <types> â†’ comma-separated file extensions to search (e.g. pdf,doc,docx,xls,ppt).

    3. -l <limit> â†’ max number of files to download (e.g. 200).

    4. -n <threads> â†’ parallel download threads (speed).

    5. -o <output_dir> â†’ directory for downloaded files & metadata output.

    6. -h or --help â†’ show full help and flags (always check this on your installed version).

ðŸ”¹Practical examples

1. Quick scan for PDFs and DOCX (download up to 100 files):

   metagoofil -d example.com -t pdf,docx -l 100 -n 10 -o /tmp/metagoofil_example

2. Broader run (more file types):

   metagoofil -d example.com -t pdf,doc,docx,xls,xlsx,ppt,pptx -l 300 -n 20 -o ./metagoofil_results

After a run youâ€™ll find:

    Downloaded documents in ./metagoofil_results/

    Extracted metadata files (usually plain text / HTML) summarizing authors, software, usernames, email addresses, and full exiftool outputs.
